The '''Kingdom of Benin'''<ref>{{Cite web |title=What was the Kingdom of Benin? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bitesize/articles/z3n7mp3 |access-date=2024-06-19 |website=BBC Bitesize |language=en-GB}}</ref> or '''Empire of Benin''',<ref>{{Cite book |last=Martin |first=J. P. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OagaDgAAQBAJ&dq=%22the+Empire+of+Benin%22&pg=PT63 |title=African Empires: Volume 2: Your Guide to the Historical Record of Africa |date=2017-02-06 |publisher=Trafford Publishing |isbn=978-1-4907-7981-2 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Oronsaye |first=Daniel Nabuleleorogie |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KakuAQAAIAAJ |title=The History of Ancient Benin Kingdom and Empire |date=1995 |publisher=D.N. Oronsaye |isbn=978-978-33276-1-0 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=DK |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WW60EAAAQBAJ&dq=%22empire+of+benin%22&pg=PA183 |title=History: The Definitive Visual Guide |date=2023-04-20 |publisher=Dorling Kindersley Limited |isbn=978-0-241-64318-1 |language=en}}</ref> also known as '''Great Benin''', is a traditional kingdom in southern [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Bradbury |first=Robert Elwyn |author-link=Robert Elwyn Bradbury |chapter=Continuities and Discontinuities in Pre-colonial and Colonial Benin Politics (1897–1951) |title=Benin Studies |editor-last=Morton-Williams |editor-first=Peter |date=1973 |pages=76–128 |publisher=Routledge |doi=10.4324/9781351031264-4 |isbn=978-1-351-03126-4 |s2cid=159119713 }}</ref> It has no historical relation to the modern republic of [[Benin]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=The kingdom of Benin |language=en-GB |work=BBC Bitesize |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bitesize/topics/zpvckqt/articles/z3n7mp3 |access-date=2022-12-19}}</ref> which was known as [[Dahomey]] from the 17th century until 1975. The Kingdom of Benin's capital was Edo, now known as [[Benin City]] in [[Edo State]], [[Nigeria]]. The Benin Kingdom was one of the oldest and most developed [[State (polity)|states]] in the coastal hinterland of [[West Africa]]. It grew out of the previous [[Edo people|Edo]] Kingdom of [[Igodomigodo]] around the 11th century AD;{{sfn|Strayer|2013|pp=695-696}} it was annexed by the [[British Empire]] in 1897, but endured as a [[non-sovereign monarchy]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Kingdom of Benin {{!}} National Geographic Society |url=https://education.nationalgeographic.org/resource/kingdom-benin |access-date=2022-12-19 |website=education.nationalgeographic.org}}</ref>

In the 15th and 16th centuries, the empire reached the height of its prosperity, expanding its territory, trading with European powers, and creating a remarkable artistic legacy in cast bronze, iron, brass, carved ivory, and other materials.<ref name=":5"></ref>

